textDisplay:
Are prisons made just to prevent the criminal from committing the crime again? Or are they made to punish the criminal for what he did?

You can only prevent a criminal from doing something if it's a crime that the criminal may want or need to commit multiple times.

You can only rehabilitate the criminal if the crime was not committed exactly for reasons of his character.


If your wife cheats on you with your business partner and you kill both.
You will not repeat the crime anyway. So there is no need to keep you in prison.

And it's not something you are rehabilitated from. It was a one time event where you lost your mind.


So it's clear prison in those cases serve as punishment and as society's way to tell other people "don't commit crimes, or you will lose your freedom and the penalty is heavy"


How can the Finnish system deal with such cases?

If you have nothing to lose, you might very well commit the crime and learn new crimes

textDisplay: As a species, we have to ask ourselves, do we work to treat the cause of crime? Or do we just punish those that commit it for the sake of revenge? As emotional animals, we tend to favour revenge, but an eye for an eye makes the whole world blind and if we're all blind we can not see the solution to our problems. The key in medicine is not treatment, it is prevention, and that is how we should deal with crime, not by putting more police on the streets to catch criminals but by putting teachers in classrooms and educating citizens and making sure they have the best start possible in their life. In medicine, you don't treat the symptoms, you treat the disease and crime is just the symptom of a society that has abandoned people, a society that is suffering from inequality where having food on the table depends on who your parents were.

textDisplay:
I'm conflicted on this. On one hand, this system seems to work and it'll benefit society. Imagine the contributions they might make in Finland after gaining the knowledge and passions needed to establish new businesses. By comparison, our antiquated and privatized prison system in America only serves to tax us so criminals can be shoved far away from society and if released, just return back in less than a year.

On the other hand, it feels like it encourages bad behavior if prison is better than normal societal living. And for victims it's gut-wrenching to know they'll never get to satiate their emotional need for revenge.

I suppose this works well in Finland because it's layered with the other great government programs they offer. As much as it pains me to say, America's too far behind for a switch like this to bear any good fruit, I think. For now anyways.

textDisplay:
I know people are mocking this style, yet at the end of it all it is an effective method, given in an environment like this, their situation is much more ideal. Along with their being productive, over being just stuck in a cell and told to stare at the wall. Which is why jails in the U.S. tend to fail hard, as criminals want nothing other than to get out. Along with basically not being rehabilitated for their behavior or the reason why they landed in prison. With this system it makes them both not want to break out, along with when they do eventually get out they can integrate into society better and easier, meaning their less likely to go back to prison. Compare to the U.S. to where prisoners that may of been in jail for 15-30 years, missed all the innovation and growth the world has gone through, and it puts them in a scary situation to them. Given the world as they knew it is completely different now, and it makes the failure rate higher and means our jails are bloated as a result.

I agree that for some this wouldn't work, like drug or gang lords that simply would escape at their first opportunity. Yet for a lot of lower tier criminals this would work and would incentives them to turn their life around, while also making sure their kept up with the evolving world outside of them, and can have a decent future when they get out. Over being thrust into a bad situation with no where to go, other than going back to jail again.

While I find the process and concept interesting, I must admit that many of your numbers are skewed and have a fair bit of bias. With your numbers, 1% of the US population is in prison and 0.05% of Finlands population is in prison. I'm pretty sure you are just splitting hairs.
FInland has little to no diversity in its racial and ethnic groups. 94% are "White" Finnish with the 5% are from mostly European countries and 1% from Asia . Finland is a homogeneous country while the US is a melting pot of people from all over the world. You see people that are different from you and come from different places.
How many Finnish people see a person of a different skin color or speak a different language on a daily basis?

textDisplay: They should just get rid of prisons and give people a certain amount of times they can break serious laws with the punishment being the death penalty after like 50 misdemeanors. 1 serious crime like murder will just be instant death. Private prisons are a industry and have very little to do with rehabilitation. I joke by saying "we don't have gulags in the United States just look at the prison system." Only problem though is that the people writing the laws could abuse their power to make stupid laws for people to break. Basically no murder or rapes because they'll just get the death penalty. They can even add a system where small misdemeanors can get scrubbed off their record. Our prison system is abused to the point where people are sitting in jail for 10 years for a bag of weed. For smaller crimes you can still punish them and remove a point from them but like I said no matter what you have it's subject to tyrannical abuse. For example like making it a misdemeanor to steal a propaganda poster like in North Korea. We all know what happened to Otto Warmbier. Just saying, theirs a 1,000 better ways than the American prison system. Imagine 3 misdemeanors for smoking pot and rotting in jail for 10 years so the owners can get free labor. Small crimes should be redeemable with a warning and the knowledge that if you keep committing small crimes you'll wind up dead. If you do that you can get rid of most of the stupid laws like J-Walking and disturbing the peace. People should be allowed to do what they want for the most part as long as they're not hurting anybody. You should need to prove that the persons actions caused harm to another person before you give them a infraction and if the person who was allegedly harmed decides to not charge them it gets dropped. Just to avoid legalese like "Your selling drugs on the street killed a person." that's a bunch of crap because people are capable of making their own decisions. I believe people are ultimately responsible for their own decisions in the case of selling drugs. I think the people pushing the vaccine believe the same thing. It's a little different with the vaccine though because they're forcing it. If I said "here's a bag of heroin and if you don't eat all of it you can't work or shop at the grocery store" then that's different. I also believe that the private prison system has a conflict of interest with the justice system.

textDisplay:
Cruel, punitive treatment of prisoners does not rehabilitate them; it makes them more likely to commit further crime. On the other hand, it does not help the victims of crimes, either—research shows the most effective way to help the victims is for the perpetrator to make direct payments to them, which is impossible to do on prison wages.

So, who does this kind of treatment help? It helps prisons make money.

I find most people who have a problem with evidence-based rehabilitation are people who have never actually been the victim of a crime. And those that are, are blinded by emotion. If I can see past the hate, so can you.

textDisplay: I think that people forget that when we put someone in prison, we have to pay to keep them in prison. At the point someone is in prison (assuming they are rightfully found guilty) all crime prevention efforts have, by definition, failed them; therefore, it makes perfect sense from an efficiency standpoint to use the time we have these people captive to focus on reducing their risk of recidivism. I happen to believe that a prisoner's sentence should not implicitly  come with "and start from economic rock bottom right when you get out" attached to their year count, but it's worth remembering that reintegrating someone into society is an infinitely more positive outcome for that society than further isolating them as punishment for their deviation.
textOriginal: I think that people forget that when we put someone in prison, we have to pay to keep them in prison. At the point someone is in prison (assuming they are rightfully found guilty) all crime prevention efforts have, by definition, failed them; therefore, it makes perfect sense from an efficiency standpoint to use the time we have these people captive to focus on reducing their risk of recidivism. I happen to believe that a prisoner's sentence should not implicitly  come with "and start from economic rock bottom right when you get out" attached to their year count, but it's worth remembering that reintegrating someone into society is an infinitely more positive outcome for that society than further isolating them as punishment for their deviation.

textDisplay:
While this prison system gives the impression that prisoners are free civilians..they are not.

Those who commit serious crimes in Finland go into a regular closed prison where they spend their time in a small confined room. It is only after 15-20 years in prison that they are put into the open prison system and only if the prisoner had perfect conduct in the closed prison. Open prison inmates are very carefully selected.

And Those who commit lesser crimes may never see an open prison, they will be released from prison before they have the chance to get selected for an open prison. Inmates have to prove themself in a normal prison for them to be selected into the open prison system.

textDisplay: Many do not realize that the Finnish penal system is of such high standard that this approach is actually a cost-saving strategy by Finland. In recent news (October 2021) the daily costs for an incarcerated inmate runs in the high €200 (€80,000+ annually), a stay in 5 star hotel was cheaper! The pandemic made the costs even higher so the system has to place more inmates to programs such as these (out-of cell) to save on money. It even "influenced" the serving and handing of sentences to current on going cases of convicts/criminals, from delaying of sentencing to "lighter" punishments (house arrest/probations instead of incarceration etc) Imagine that.

textDisplay:
So, people go to jail for a lot of reasons. If life in prison is as good as or better than life outside of prison, what is the reason to not commit a crime? Indeed, in America, it's a thing that people re-offend for the "three hots and a cot". If the government is taking 50% of your income OR you can't make enough wages to secure your three hots, etc, what keeps you from commiting crimes, either to have a better standard of living in one case or because there is not enough of a consequence to your standard of living to overcome impulsive crimes?
The sweet spot seems to sit between enough of a deterrent to stop those who are able from committing those crimes while still providing enough humanity and rehabilitation that someone isnt just revolving between the street and the cell.
If it's so great inside those prisons, then why aren't Finnish criminals dying to get back to prison?
And do you want the government to take up to 62 percent of your pay so that criminals can have a more pleasant stay in jail?
It doesn't make sense to me. I suspect that not all the facts are perfectly clear. Either jail isn't as pleasant as is portrayed or more people are returning to jail than is reported.
Also, when comparing Finland to America, please remember that 327 million more people live in America than Finland. Also, Finland is a much more homogeneous country than America and good citizen values are more likely to be shared by others.
Don't get me wrong, it sounds lovely. We all want to live in a society that guarantees our needs and our safety. It's just not a simple comparison of one or two variables. There are a LOT of difficult to control variables in how to address crime and recidivism in different countries.

textDisplay: While there are tonnes of evidence to support rehabilitation being beneficial, you have to consider how difficult it would be to generalise what we've seen here to larger populations with more cultural diversity, different histories, politics, economics, etc. Let me give a general example: would it be easier to rehabilitate a Finnish man with a society that better supports and nurtures him (free healthcare, college tuition, etc) than an American man living in a population ~60 times greater, with fewer job opportunities, no free healthcare, tuition or other support, living in a community where there is a high affinity for gang violence and membership? And that's not to mention that the looming fear of tough disciplinary action plays a fundamental role in many individuals abstaining from criminal acts, therefore the knowledge that prison life is somewhat comfortable may encourage them to act antisocially without said fears. While I do agree that many features of the Finnish prison rehabilitation system could apply to many people, there is still a plethora of factors that need to be taken into account when translating these practices to other parts of the world.
textOriginal: While there are tonnes of evidence to support rehabilitation being beneficial, you have to consider how difficult it would be to generalise what we've seen here to larger populations with more cultural diversity, different histories, politics, economics, etc. Let me give a general example: would it be easier to rehabilitate a Finnish man with a society that better supports and nurtures him (free healthcare, college tuition, etc) than an American man living in a population ~60 times greater, with fewer job opportunities, no free healthcare, tuition or other support, living in a community where there is a high affinity for gang violence and membership? And that's not to mention that the looming fear of tough disciplinary action plays a fundamental role in many individuals abstaining from criminal acts, therefore the knowledge that prison life is somewhat comfortable may encourage them to act antisocially without said fears. While I do agree that many features of the Finnish prison rehabilitation system could apply to many people, there is still a plethora of factors that need to be taken into account when translating these practices to other parts of the world.

textDisplay: Finland is ~93% Finnish natives, an almost homogeneous demographic. For a country that does not invite the 3rd world into the country unchecked, it makes sense that they are capable of reducing the isolation and severity of their prisons. Unfortunately, the USA is full of gangs of every race and nationality, and if we ended the prison system here, it would lead to an unmanageable uptick in all kinds of crime. The drug war, on the other hand, needs to end, because addicts are not inherently criminal. That would cut the prison population in the USA roughly in half. The reason we have so many people in our prisons is because of unreasonable drug laws, undoubtedly worsened by Joe Biden's 1994 crime bill.

textDisplay: Tons of reasons why we can't copy this exact system, but I think the biggest one is people's views on justice and the severity of crime that people more often deal with. Many people believe more in justice than in rehabilitation, I mean obviously most of us have the moral compass to let drug users and thieves get a second chance, but a first degree murderer, or a drunk driver? It's a completely different outlook to look at someone who robbed someone's opportunity at living their life to the fullest, and rather than wish for atonement or punishment, they're given the assurance that at least one life will walk away better off, and hopefully reformed. And while I agree that the US prison system needs massive change, and that there's a lot of screwed up things about them, there are many people who argue otherwise that "It should never be about punishment, look at the statistics!" They haven't felt the kind of grief that others have. And for those that do, most wouldn't feel safe knowing that the one who took their loved one's chance at life will walk free in 10 years time with a job, opportunities, and a place in the society that failed to protect a victim of a crime--but sure as hell succeeded in protecting the perpetrator. Now some are perfectly happy with the system in Finland, some think that 15 years in a place like that is good enough and they feel safe, but they are a very privileged society--they have a primarily homogenous culture, with a very healthy economy without the huge economic disparities seen in the US--meaning there's very little to reason to turn to a life of crime to begin with. So it's uncommon to fear walking alone on the sidewalk in an urban center even during the day, with the fear of getting stabbed or mugged. In grave contrast, in some areas of the US, it's all too common. And when we fear something, we hate it. People in the US don't see crime as a logical problem that needs to be fixed, it's rather about righting what's been wronged--"the meek shall inherit." It sounds silly until you realize it can happen to you, and your ideals are challenged at their core, as it did to me. I really hope we get far with reforms in the future but now I understand and empathize with why so many are resistant to the ideal of rehabilitation over punishment.

And for those that do, most wouldn't feel safe knowing that the one who took their loved one's chance at life will walk free in 10 years time with a job, opportunities, and a place in the society that failed to protect a victim of a crime--but sure as hell succeeded in protecting the perpetrator. Now some are perfectly happy with the system in Finland, some think that 15 years in a place like that is good enough and they feel safe, but they are a very privileged society--they have a primarily homogenous culture, with a very healthy economy without the huge economic disparities seen in the US--meaning there's very little to reason to turn to a life of crime to begin with. So it's uncommon to fear walking alone on the sidewalk in an urban center even during the day, with the fear of getting stabbed or mugged.
